{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_endive_ver02/data/sn86063811/00279558388/1937120201/0349.xml":{"full_text":"WEATHER\nPartly cloudy tonight and Fri\nday, slightly colder tonight.\n<2\n<Dtr \u00a9tmes\nLargest Daily Circulation of Any Newspaper in North Carolina in Proportion to Population\nGOOD AFTERNOON\n\u2022Under dictatorship, the aver\nage citizen's life it ju\u00bbt li*d up in\na series of \"not*.\"\nVOL. 56\u2014No. 288\nHENDERSONVILLE, N. C., THURSDAY, DECEMBER 2, 1937\nWAGES-HOURS BILL IS FORCED TO FLOOR\n9 V\nThink Sino-Jap Peace May Be In Making\nNAZI ENVOY'S\nNANKING VISIT\nIS SIGNIFICANT\nRussia Shipping War Ma\nterials by Air Into\nChina\nSOUTH CHINA DRIVE\nBY JAPAN IS SEEN\nBULLETIN\nSHANGHAI. Dec. 2. (UP)\u2014 j\nA report today said that Gen\neralissimo Chiang Kai-shek has\nordered the destruction of har\nbor bridges and the Japanese\nmills of Tsingtao, rich port on\nthe Yellow sea.\n(Copyright, 1937, United Press)\nSHANGHAI, Dec. 2.\u2014 (UP)\u2014\nImportant political developments,\npossibly involving the initiation of\npeace conferences between China\nand Japan arc reported today in\ndispatches from scattered parts of\nChina.\nDiplomats attached consider\nable importance to the Nanking\nvisit of Dr. Oscar P. Trautman,\nGerman ambassador to China.\nGeneralissimo Chiang Kai-shek\nof China is in Nanking, although\nall other Chinese government of\nficials had departed.\nDiplomats considered it \"not\nimprobable\" that peace ef.'orts\nare to bu made, maybe by China\nherself, before Nanking falls.\nMeantime at Hankow China and\nSoviet Russian officials asserted\nthat Chinese armies were receiv\ning war materials from Russia by\nairplane by way of Chinese Tur\nkestan.\nRussia is known to be interest\ned in the Chinese cause.\nA month ago Russia's General\nVassily Bleucher said. \"Fascism's\noffenses ugainst the Chinese peo\nples is in preparation for an at\ntack on the Soviet Union. Russia\nis prepared, if necessary, to car\nry on war beyond its boundaries,\nif necessary to protect her inter\nests.\"\nRussian sources said that ma\nterials are easily moved from Rus\nsia to China in 40 hours.\nJapan today was reported to\nhave landed 50,000 soldiers in\nSouth China in an apparent drive\non the great metropolis of Can\nton. a principal source of Chinese\nmilitary supplies.\nForeign military attaches said\nthat if Canton is taken a vital\nblow will be struck at the hujre\ntrade of the British crown colony\nof Hongkong and already tense\nrelations between London and\nTokyo, strained further.\nHongkong exists almost exclus\nively on commerce with Canton\nthe financial and commercial cen\n(Continued on pajje five)\nOfficial Work And\nFishing, Consume\nRoosevelt's Time\nMIAMI. Fla.. Pec. 2. (UP).\u2014\nPresident Roosevelt is enjoying\nexcellent luck in his fishing oft'\nDry Tortugas near Key West on\nhis yacht. Potomac. The yacht\nwill remain anchoret! there an\nother 24 hours, so all the mem\nbers of the vacation party can\nget their fili of angling.\nMIAMI. Fla., Dec. 2. (f.*P)\nPresident Roosovelt remained off\nDry Tortugas near Key West last\nnight after a day devoted mostly\nto work aboard the yacht Potomac\nwith a few nours of fishing sand\nwiched in.\nThe chief executive scanned of\nficial mail and documents flown\nto the yacht Potomac by navy sea\nplane and spent the entire fore\nnoon clearing away government\nbusiness ili order that the flyers\ncould come back to their Miami\nbase with a full return cargo i f\nletters.\nA dispatch received at tempo\nrary White House offices in the\nMiami-Biltmore hotel gave the\nfollowing insight into activities\naboard the Potomac:\n\"Will stay here (Garden Kiy.\nDry Tortugas) so that the presi\ndent can enjoy excellent tishitur.\nPlane with work for the president\narcived noon and the president\nspent morning clearing as much\nas possible before return flight.\nNo other news at present.\"\nThe radio message was signed\nby James fcoosevelt. who, with\nSecretary lckes, Harry Hopkins\nand others, is the guest of the\npresident.\nCOMPLETE REVISION OF LABOR\nRELATIONS ACT IS URGED BY\nWEIR OF NATIONAL STEEL CORP.\nCHICAGO. Dec. 4UP)\u2014Br.'\nnest Weir. chairman of the Na\ntional Steel corporation. today\ncharged that the administration\nand labor leaders are responsible\nfor th eiinsettlfd labor conditions\nand lilted a complete revision of\nthe* National Labor Relations act\nas i he first step toward a remedy.\nSecretary of Commerce Daniel\nC Roper admitted frankly last\nni*rht the \"experimental\" nature\nof the administration's undistrib\nuted corporate canting* tax and\nassured business men that con\njfi'ess ami the treasury already\nwere working to eliminate \"any\ninjustices in our tax laws.\"\nRoper's address, delivered be\nfore the business advisory coun\ncil. was interpreted as an admin\nistration reply to charges that\n\"uncertainty\" as to New Deal pol\nicy was an \"important contribut\ning factor in the hesitancy of in\nvestors and business leaders\" to\nmake those investments believed\nnecessary to stable prosperity.\nThe charges were contained in\na report of the council, composed\nof approximately (id industrial\nleaders, to the department of com\nmerce and President Roosevelt.\nThe president sent his vri\"v?ftir\u00bbK^\nto the council and said:\n\"1 am looking forward to meet\ning with ull of you at the earliest\npracticable date so we may have\nthe opportunity of talking over!\nproblem* that affect all of us so\nvitally. 1 am confident that appro- i\npriate action can lead to inereas-1\ned employment and more effec\ntive purchasing power in the\nhands of great masses of people\nstill without adequate income.\"\nKopcr defended the undistrib\nuted earnings tax as an \"admit\ntedly experimental\" move to\n\"bring about a higher velocity of\nmoney through larger and more\nwidespread distribution of corpor\nate earnings, which, in some out\nstanding cases, had been retained\nas excessive surplus funds.\"\n'WINDOW SHOPPING' EVENT\nSET HERE FOR FRIDAY NIGHT\nNOVEMBER DRY)\nAND COLD HERE\nTemperature of 10 Degs.\nIs Low; Average 3 Degs.\nUnder Normal\nNovember was a cold, dry\nmonth, the summary of official\nweather figures shows. The mean\ntemperature for the month was\n43.1 degrees, and only 1.51 in\nches of rainfall were recorded.\nThe normal mean temperature\nfor November is 46.4 degrees and\nth\u00bb* normal rainfall is 3.11 inches.\nA mean minimum temperature\nof 30.7 degrees was recorded for\nthe month, almost two degrees\nbelow freezing, and temperatures\nof 17, 11, 13, 10, iy, were re\n1 corded on successive days.\nThe summary for the month is\nas follows:\nMean max.\u201455.5 degrees.\nMean min.\u201430.7 degrees.\nMean\u201443.1 degrees.\nNormal mean\u201446.4 degrees.\nMaximum\u201473 degrees on 2nd.\nMinimum\u201410 degrees on 23rd.\nMean daily range\u20142-1.7 de\ngrees.\nGreatest daily range\u2014n de\ngrees on 7th.\nRainfall\u20141.51 inches.\nNormal rainfall\u20143.11 inches.\nNo. days of rainfall\u201412.\nClear days\u201419.\ni Partly cloudy\u20146.\nCloudy\u20145.\nWEDNESDAY\nMaximum\u201455 degrees. Mini\nmum\u201422 degrees. Mean\u201438.5\nj degrees. Day's range 33 de\ngrees.\nNormal mean temperature for\nI December\u20143D.3 degrees. Normal\nrainfall for December\u20145.46 in\nches.\nFORD CITED BY\nLABORJOARD\nComplaint on File Is Based\non Accusations Made\nby C.I.O.\nST. LOUIS. Dec. 2. (UP).\u2014\nThe Ford Motor company was\ncited yesterday to appear here\nbefore the national labor rela\ntions board December 16 to an\nswer charges uf unfair labor\npractices at its local assembly\nplant, where a .strike called by\nthe United Automobile Workers\nof America is in its second week.\nThe complaint, filed with the\nregional office of the labor\nboard, was based on accusations\nmade by the C.I.O. union.\nIt is charged that the company\n\"interferred with, restrained and\ncoerced its employes in the ex\n1 ercise of their rights of self\norganization\" and threatened to\n\"discharge employes who refuse;\nor refused to sign statements\nthey are or were satisfied with\ntheir conditions of employment1\nand the labor policy of the com\npany.\"\nWill Be Featured by Dis\ntribution of Over $200\nin Gifts\nHcntWrsonvillo merchants will\ninaugurate the Christmas shop\nping period here on Friday night,\nwhich will be observed as \"win\ndow shopping night,\" and will be\nfeatured by the distribution of\nmore than $200 in gift certifi\ncates, and the turning on of the\ncity's street lighting system.\nMerchants of the city today\nwithout exception were busily en\ngaged in preparing for the Christ\nina* season. Stores were taking\n3n a holiday air, decorations\nwere being installed, and Christ\nmas merchandise was being at\ntractively arranged.\nMayor A. V. Edwards an\nnounced this morning that all ar\nrangements had been completed\nto turn on the gaily colored street\nlights on Friday night at 7\no'clock. The colorless bulbs in\nthe lights at present will be re\nmoved and the colored lights in\nstalled. In addition merchants\nplanned to use much outside dec\norating material, and the city\nwill be dressed in holiday attire\nby Friday night.\nAt the Chamber of Commerce\noffice this morning it was an\nnounced that merchants had sign\ned 210 of the gift certificates,\neach worth one dollar in merchan\ndise if used on Saturday, Dec. 4,\nthe day after the shopping night.\nThese certificates will be dis\ntributed in the crowd of window\nshoppers on Friday night. Uni\ndentified persons will mingle with\nthe crowds on the streets on Fri\nday night and pass out the cer\ntificates.\ntificates. The certificates will be\ngiven only to persons looking in\nstore windows between 7 and 1)\no'clock.\nThe Hendersonville high school\nband will play during the window\nshopping period.\nNAVAL PLANE\n2 MENJISSING\nSearch Made on Land and\nSea in the Virginia\nBeach Section\nNORFOLK, Va., Dec. 2. (UP).\nNavy nirplanes, coastguard cut\nters and land parties today con\ntinued to search for Cadet Jas. J.\nJones, Washington, and Machinist\nTroy Blanton, LaFayette, Ala.,\nlost when their plane crashed\nover the Atlantic, off Virginia\nBeach, last night.\nWreckage of the pla,ne was\nwashed ashore. It was believed\nthe occupants jumped in para\nchutes or took to the sea with\nlife preservers. Officials say the\nsearch is to go on till the fliers\nor their bodies are found.\nRALPH HENDRIX BETTER\nThe condition of Kalph Hen\ndrix, who is ill at Patton Memor\nial hospital, was reported as im\nproved today, friends will be\nglad to learn.\nTAX REVISIONS\nARE VIRTUALLY\nREADY. IS SAID\n\"Shake up\" in Estate and\nGift Levies Would Net\nU. S. $25,000,000\nAVERAGE TAXPAYER\nSAID UNAFFECTED\nWASHINGTON\". Dec. 2. (UP)\nTax lew revisions to encourage\nbusiness revival virtually were j\ncompleted yesterday with a tenta\ntive agreement by a house ways\nand means sub-committee on a\n\"shake-up\" in levies on estates\nand Kifts which experts estimated\nwould swell treasury receipts $15,\n000.000 to $25,000,000 annually.\nThe proposed changes would es\ntablish a new set of rates on es-1\ntales ranging from per cent on\n$50,000 to 70.3 per cent on $100,- j\n000,000; would consolidate the;\npresent 140,000 gift and $40,000\nestate tax exemptions and permit\nonly one exemption of 10,000 in\nboth categories and would lower\nfrom $5,000 to $3,000 per year\nthe irift tax on an individual.\nUnder the present law the es\ntate taxes range from 2 per cent\non the first $10,000 >f taxable in\ncome to 70 per cent on fortunes\nin excess of $50,000,000. The gift\ntax is three quarters of the estate\nlevy. The new plan projects a\nschedule of taxes to be applied to\nthe total estate and exempts the\nfirst $40,000 from taxation.\nChairman Fred Vinson. P., Kv.,\nof the sub-committee otld newspa\nper reporters that the proposed\nchanges will not impose higher\nlevies on the average taxpayer but\nhe explained that the government\nwould obtain additional revenue\nthrough simplification of the law\nand through lowering of exemp\ntions.\nWith its task almost completed,\nthe sub-committee discussed the\nproblem of imposing federal taxes\nupon hundreds of thousands of\nstate and municipal executives\nand employes whose salaries now\ncannot be touched by the govern\nment. Vinson sought to correct\nthe impression that the salaries of\nfederal employes or executives are\nfree from federal taxes, pointing\nout that even President Roosevelt\nmust pay. Federal salaries, how\never, cannot be taxed by states\nor cities.\nNo accurate estimate yet has\nbeen reached by the amount of\nrevenue the treasury will lose or\ngain through the tax changes soon\nto be submitted to the house. They\n(Continued on page five)\nMrs. Mabel Brown\nGiven Judgment\nAgainst Estate\nMrs. Mabel Brown won judg\nment of $2010 in an action in\nsuperior court yesterday after\nnoon from Norman Miller, admin\nistrator of the estate of Elniira\nJ. Miller, deceased.\nMrs. Brown, the daughter of\nMrs. Miller and sister of Mr. Mil\nler, the administrator, sought to\nrecover from her mother's estate\nfor financial assistance allegedly\ngiven prior to her death.\nExpert Witness Says Tennessee Can\nBe Made Navigable To Paducah\nFor One-Sixth f VA Planned Outlay\nCHATTANOOGA, Tenn., Dec.\n2.\u2014(UP)\u2014An expert witness,\nConsulting Engineer Rufus W.\nPutnum, Chicago, yesterday told\na three-judge federal court that\nthe Tennessee river could be\nmade navigable with a 0-foot\nchannel from Paducah, Ky., to\nKnoxville, Tenn., for one-sixth the\ncost of the Tennessee Valley au\nthority program.\nPutnam's plan for developing\nthe river for navigation provided\nfor construction of low, non-pow\ner dams the same as recom\nmended by the chief of U. S. en\ngineers in 1930 whereas the\nT\\'A program specifies high dams\nfor generation of large quantities\nof cheap \"yardstick\" electrical\npower.\nThe consulting engineer, a rud\ndy-faced man in his 40's, who re\nsigned as U. S. engineer of the\nChicago district in 192C, took a\nsuitcase of data to the witness\nstand and testified in a crisp, mil\nitary voice for six hours.\nHe was the first expert witness\ncalled by the 18 southeastern util\nities making: the second federal\ncourt fight against the constitu\ntionality of the TVA.\nExcluding the Wilson dam and\ntwo other small ones which ex\nisted before the TVA was created\nin 1933, Putnam estimated a sys\ntem of low dams would cost $75.\n000.000 as compared to the esti\nmated cost of $473,650,000 for\nthe TVA project of combination\npower and navigation dams.\nThe witness further stated that\nhe present freight waterway traf\nfic, or the traffic which might be\nexpected \"reasonably\" within 30\nyears after creation of the 0-foot\nchannel, for the entire length of.\nthe Tennessee river, would justify\na capital investment of between\n$35,000,000 and $47,365,000, a\n(Continued on page five) i\nROOSEVELT PARTY GANGS UP ON THE FISH\nMaybe you think this i :i hunch of high-powered federal executives ubout to hold a conference. Hon\ne.tly, though, it's jn.-.t a hunch of the boys from Wa.-hington aboard the U. S. S. Potomac at Miami,\nFla.. waiting t(\u00bb oil on a lishinK trip. Left to right the Izaak Waltons are, standing. Captain Wal\nter B. Woodson, naval aide; Assistant Attorney General Robert Jackson; WPA Administrator Harry\nHopkins; and 1 \u00bbr. Ross Mclntyre; seated, Presidcn; Roosevelt and Harold L. Ickes, Secretary of the\nInterior.\nFOUR CIO MEN\nESCORTED OUT\nOF ASHEVILLE\nStep Follows Workers' In\nvitation to Men to Leave\nHosiery Mill\nASHEVILLE. Doc. 2.\u2014A.she\nville city police officers last night\nescort od four CIO organizers\nfrom a hotel to the city limits\nwhen a crowd of about 100 hos\niery employes sought to ^ain en\ntrance to the rooms occupied by\nthe men.\nThe incident came after trouble\nearlier in the day at the hosiery\nmill when eight alleged organizers\nof the CIO were asked to leave\nthe mill by workers. Spokesmen\nfor the workers said they escorted\nthe men to the mill door and told\nthem tu get out of the building.\nCompany officials said they were\nnot at the mil! at the time and\nknew nothing of the trouble.\nLast night a crowd gathered at\nthe hotel, but was dispersed by\nofficers, who escorted the men to\nthe city limits and took the eight\nmen ejected from the mill out of\na side door. The men escorted to\nthe city limits said they were\ning to Spartanburg. S. C.\nSOVIET POLAR ICE CAMP IS\nTHREATENED WITH BREAK UP\nDrifts Rapidly Toward\nGreenland, Over 600\nMiles From Pole\nLONDON, Dec. 2. (UP)\u2014The\nSoviet \"Polar\" camp of four men,\nwho have been livinic on an ice\nfloe since last May 21, is drifting\nrapidly toward Greenland more\nthan 600 miles from the North\nPole and is in danger of breaking\nup, the party .said in a radio mes\nsage picked up by the Daily Ex\npress today.\n\"We are now over 600 miles\nfrom the pole and have had to\nbattle with many difficulties,\" Ivan\nPapanin, leader of the expedition,\nradioed to Petrozavodsk.\n\"We are approaching the shores\nof Greenland and must be ready\nat any moment to face another\ngrim problem\u2014how to carry on\namid crushing ice.\"\nThe other three members of the\ncamp are Ernest Krenkel, radio\noperator who participated in the\nfamed Chelyuski rescue expedi\ntion Pytor SbairshofT and Eugene\nFeodoroff, experts in Arctic ex\nploration.\nThe party, which landed 15\nmiles beyond the pole by plane,\nhas been drifting several miles a\nday ever since. The men erected\n(Continued on page eight)\nBand and Choral\nClub Concert Set\nFor December 9\nTickets Placed on Sale To\nday; to Swell Fund\nfor H. S. Band,\nAnnouncement was made today\nthat tickets were on sale for the\nforthcominir concert to be given\nby the Civic Choral club and the\nHendersonville high school band,\nat the high school auditorium the\nnight of Thursday, Dec. 9th. The\nprogram will open at 8:15 o'clock.\nA varied and attractive pro\ngram of selections in being pre\npared for the choral club under\nthe direction of Alva H. Lowe,\nand will include classic and popu\nlar selections.\nTickets are to be had at the\nEconomv Drug company, or from\nschool students, who are selling\nthem in view of the fact that the\nhigh school band will participate\nin the proceeds which they will\nuse for the purchase of equipment\nand music. I\nCANCELLING OF\nFEDERAL ROAD\nAID OPPOSED\nSouthern Spokesmen Give\nViews; Said Not Favored\nin Congress\nNEW ORLEANS, Doc. 2. (UP).\nPresident Roosevelt's suggested\nchange in existing laws granting\nfederal aid for road construction\nlast night drew protests from\nSenator Pat Harrison that con\ngress is not in sentiment with the\nsuggestion.\nHarrison, D., Miss., and chair\nman of the powerful senate fi\nnance committee, telegraphed\nGovernor Hugh White that he is\n\"not in sympathy with the presi\ndent's program\" and that as far\nas he ascertains \"there is no senti\nment in congress to have the\npresident's suggestion made ef\nfective.\"\nGovernor White communicated\nhis and the highway commission'*\nviews to Harrison and their esti\nmates of the difficulties the pro\nposal would impose upon Missis\nsippi's completing its current\n$42,000,000 highway program.\nMeanwhile, L. P. Abernathy,\nchairman of the Louisiana high\nway commissioners, said enact\nment of the plan to curtail fed\neral aid for highways would re\nsult in loss of $3,000,000 to\nLouisiana. Such action would se\nverely hamper the highway pro\ngram, he said, including farm-to\nmarket roads and grade crossing\nconstruction.\nFATHER POSTS BOND\nPHILADELPHIA, Dec. 2. (UP)\nMary Keenan O'Connor, 19-year\nold college girl charged with hom\nicide in the Labor day death of\nNancy Glenn, 6, was released\nfrom Moyamensing prison last\nnight after her father posted\n$5,000 bond for her appearance\nin court.\nSHIP IN 84TH YEAR\nMELOURNE! (UP). The\nEdina, one of the oldest steam\nships in the world, haa jjust be\ngun its 84th year of service on\nPort Phillip bay. It served as a\ntroop ship in the Crimean war.\nCAMPAIGN WON\nTO DISCHARGE\nCOMMITTEE\nMcNary Urges Senate io\nRecommit Hastily Drawn\nFarm Measure\nSTATES ROOSEVELT\nWOULD VETO BILL\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 2. (UP;\nThe administration today won it*\nfight to free the wages and hour*\nbill from the house rules commit\ntee which had pigeonholed tbtt\nmeasure last August. A total of\n218 representatives affixed their\nnaines to the petition, discharging\nthe rules committee from further\nconsideration of the bill and au\ntomatically bringing it up for con\nsideration on the floor of th<*\nhouse on December 13.\nThreats to sabotage cotton sec\ntions of the administration's vital\nfarm program last night appar\nently broke a southern blockade\nagainst consideration of the con\ntroversial bill.\nAfter a dramatic, high-pressure\ncloak-room drive in which wag\u00bb\nhour advocates plead for \"support\nof the president,\" house leaders\nlate yesterday had obtained 210\nsignatures, which was just eight\nshfrt of the necessary majority.\nThe drive brought 16 new six\nnatures yesterday and the re\nmaining necessary eight today.\nThe apparent break came after\nirate industrial and urban repre\nsentatives threatened to wreck\nthe farm bill, particularly tlx*\ncotton section, if southern con\ngressmen persisted in opposing\ntheir measure.\nHouse Majority Leader Sam\nRayburn, D., Tex., had said th\u00bb\u00ab\n\"right is won and we will have\nthe required signatures by 1 p. in.\nThursday.\" Minority Leader Bert\nrand H. Snell, R., N. Y., in turn\nagreed that the bill was headed\nfor the floor and said that \"W\u00bb\u00ab\n\u2666might as well have a show-down\nnow.\nRepresentative Martin Dies, D.,\nTex., member of the rules com\nmittee, charged the administra\ntion with trading to get the peti\ntion filed.\n\"They have traded and promif\ned member# everything to get\nthem on that petition,\" he said.\n(Continued on page eight)\nMISS MAXWELL AT\nPEN; CLEMENCY FOR\nHER IS STILL URGED\nRICHMOND, Va., Deo. 2. (UP)\nEdith Maxwell, young Wise coun\nty schoolteacher, yesterday was\ninitiated into routine at Virginia's\nstate penitentiary, where fhe is\nunder sentence of 20 years for\nkilling her father.\nPrison Superintendent R. M.\nYouell said Miss Maxwell will\nspend 10 days on a series of ex\naminations given all new prison\ners before she is assigned to work\nMeantime, Governor George C.\nPerry continued to receive a\nstream of letters urging a pardon\nfor Miss Maxwell.\nShe entered the penitentiary\nTuesday to start serving the sen\ntence imposed after she was con\nvicted for the second time in the\ndeath July 21, 1935, of 52-voar\nold Trigg Maxwell. The mountain\nteacher, then 21, contended she\nhit her father with a shoe when\nho tried to whip her for staying\nout late at night. The state su\npreme court ordered a new trial\nafter her first conviction\nCHRISTMAS\nSUPERSTITIONS\nA superstition in Central Euro\npean mining districts holds that\non Christmas Eve high mass is\nsung by invisible choristers in\nthe mine with the richest ore.\n4 5\nOA Shopping V&yi\n'fill\n>v;","height":"28026","width":"20622"}}
